UML:TaggedValue.value: -- Description -- State Electoral Division (SED) (http://www.elections.nsw.gov.au/about_elections/electoral_boundaries): A State Electoral Division is an area legally prescribed for the purpose of returning one or more members to the state or territory lower houses of parliament. Queensland has only one house of parliament at the state level, with each member representing an electoral district. An electoral district is a geographically defined area, and each district elects a representative to the Legislative Assembly. New South Wales is divided into 93 State electoral districts. Boundary management: The electoral district boundaries are determined by a distribution process which provides for an approximate equal number of electors in each electoral district. A margin of allowance of plus or minus 10% of the average enrolment is permitted.

UML:TaggedValue.value: -- Definition -- A Commonwealth Electoral Division (CED) is an area legally prescribed for the purpose of returning one or more members to the federal lower house of parliament (http://www.aec.gov.au/profiles/, there are currently 150 members and electoral divisions) A CED belongs to a specific state: this dependency is represented as a specific, cross-dataset 'UnitSpatialRelationship' between a particular CED e.g., Canberra, and a specific 'Jurisdictional Unit', e.g., ACT.
